decision_conditions:
Condition : 20 - No development excluding demolition of the early years building and enabling works to the site but including intrusive structural inspections of the roof & installation of the A/C unit for the Junior School Building, shall commence until a Construction and Environmental Management Plan (CEMP) has been submitted to and been approved in writing by the local planning authority. The CEMP shall include measures to mitigate the construction effects as part of a coordinated and collaborative approach with surrounding developments, and shall include the following details (although not limited to): 
a. the demolition of any buildings and any works to trees should take place outside of the bird nesting season (February - September (inclusive)), or if works are unavoidable during this period, then a site walk over at least 48 hours prior to works commencing is required by a named CIEEM accredited ecologist with experience of working in London to check for any nesting birds in the trees, scrub and buildings. In the event that a nest is found, an appropriate exclusion zone should be implemented around it until the young have fully fledged (Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 (as amended)). The law protects all wild bird species, their eggs and nests; 
b. details of all methods required (as identified in the Bat Emergence and Re entry Survey Report 250923 Arbtech) and timings be implemented areas of B1 and B3 identified as potential bat roost features, in order to be in accordance with the expected requirements of a European Protected Species Licence (EPSL) and / or Bat Mitigation Class Licence (BMCL). This will include but is not limited to, the type, height, orientation and location for at least one bat box to be installed on site prior to works commencing; and the details of the named CIEEM accredited ecologist with experience of working in London who will undertake the pre-commencement inspection of roost features. Works which may impact hibernating bats, will not be permitte

Condition : 22 - Notwithstanding the details shown on the approved plans and set out in the supporting information, a Landscape and Ecological Enhancement and Management Plan shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of any above ground works. The Plan shall include details of all measures to provide biodiversity gain, including but not limited to: 
a.	details of wildlife friendly planting as detailed in 141110_Broadwater SEND School Planting Schedule and Drawings numbered 141110_IBI_00_XX_PL_L_70001; 141110_IBI_00_XX_PL_L_70003
b.	details of biodiverse roofs, including details of extensive substrate base, features to be included within the substrate e.g. rope coils, logs, sand, gravel, etc., and details of any seeding/plug plant choice (in accordance with The Gro Green Roof Code 2021); 
c.	orientation, target species and location for one bat box to be installed and maintained on site during construction and a further  minimum 2 bat boxes/ bricks and bird bricks to be integrated with the new buildings; 
d.	details of a sensitive lighting scheme (including a lux levels plan) which prevents light spill onto any onsite and neighbouring habitats; do not spill onto retained nor new habitats features including integrated bat bricks and the aerial routes to and from them, in accordance with the BCT and ILP Artificial Lighting Guidance 2023 (including but not limited to LED lighting <2700 Kelvin). 
e.	details of the proposed pond including but not limited to details of submerged oxygenating species to be planted; shape, depths, structure, water source
f.	details of invertebrate and reptile habitats;
g.	details of plans to provide hedgehog boxes and allow connectivity for hedgehogs with neighbouring green spaces; 
h.	details of a management plan to be implemented for the hard and soft landscaped areas, management actions to be delivered to ensure Biodiversity Net Gain trading rules for native hedgerows can be met as well a
